subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Protoconch unknown. Teleoconch I short, smooth with weak axial growth lines (
Fig. 58A
), transition to teleoconch II marked by change in sculpture (
Fig. 58A
). Teleoconch II about 3 times length of teleoconch I, sculptured with longitudinal dextral striae (
Fig. 58C
), transition to teleoconch III marked by change in sculpture (
Figs. 58A, D
). Teleoconch III sculptured with sinuous longitudinal cords and numerous longitudinal striae (
Fig. 58F
), transition to teleoconch IV marked by incised axial line (
Fig. 58D
). Teleoconch IV sculptured with numerous sinuous, longitudinal lines (
Fig. 58I
), transition to teleoconch V marked by suture (
Fig. 59A
). Teleoconch V with identical characters as previous stage (
Fig. 58I
), transition to teleoconch VI marked by suture (
Fig. 58H
). Teleoconch VI (last growth stage) large for genus [Tol 
3.60–3.63 mm
], tubular, rather thick, mildly to moderately and regularly arched [Larc: 
1.22–1.29 mm
; Arc: 
0.25–0.28 mm
], subcylindrical with slight increase in diameter from posterior to aperture, creamy white, mottled (
Figs. 57
A–B, 58K). Surface glossy, sculptured with numerous, raised, sinuous, longitudinal cords (
Fig. 58J
). Axial sculpture of 16–20 low, rounded ribs begins centrally, rather closely arranged and regularly spaced, except last 3–4 preceding aperture, which are pronounced, widely separated (
Fig. 58K
). Axial interspaces shallow, narrower than ribs, except last 4–5 preceding aperture, which become wider (
Fig. 58K
). Posterior [Dpe: 
0.71–0.75 mm
] with thick edge, squared shoulder (
Fig. 57C
). Septum hemispherical, recessed (
Fig. 58K
). Mucro low blunt point, not visible in adult stage. Aperture [Da: 
0.90–0.99 mm
] with 3–4 pronounced axial ribs (
Fig. 58K
). No varix. Lip smooth (
Figs. 57
B–C). Periostracum thin, smooth, yellowish brown (
Fig. 57D
). Operculum thin, light brown; exterior surface with 6–7 concentric rings (
Figs. 57
G–H). Conceptual reconstruction of growth stages shown in 
Fig. 59A
.
